{
  "text": "It is relevant that our major driving force behind the studies of subtle properties of the class of P\u00f3lya-Aeppli distributions is the fact that members of this family emerge as the total number of particles of the BPS considered in [CITATION_1] , which are alive at a particular time instant t (see [9, pp. 261-262] ). Now, let us provide some more specific details. Given the parameter \u03b4 \u2208 R 1 + and the real-valued time instant t \u2208 (\u22122/\u03b4, +\u221e), set A \u03b4,t := 2\u03b4/(2 + \u03b4t). Following [CITATION_2] , we introduce a positive integer-valued parameter \u03b7. We launch our BPS from the P\u00f3lya-Aeppli distributed, random number X \u03b7,\u03b4/(2 \u221a \u03b7) of the independent particles (possibly sparsely located) at the initial time instant t = 0. In view of formula (3.5), the expected number of initial particles EX \u03b7,\u03b4/(2 \u221a \u03b7) = \u03b7. Note that the initial field here is different from those used in the majority of previous works in this area, but this assumption coincides with the specific initial field that was employed in [CITATION_3] . We elect to assume that our BPS has such P\u00f3lya-Aeppli distributed field at time t = 0 in order to be consistent with the terminology and results of [CITATION_4] . In particular, this assumption enables one to trace back this particle system to a Poisson field at time t = \u22122/\u03b4 (compare to formula (4.15) below and [9, Theorem 2.iv]). Moreover, our Corollary 4.3 below can be regarded as a local counterpart of that theorem. We refer to [9, p. 254 ] for more details on the rationale behind this choice of the initial distribution of the BPS's considered.",
  "correct_citation": {
